description.text:
A question block originally made by Matt Sauer (Forehead), which is a great design by itself and is truthful to the 8-bit inspiration, remixed with three adjustments:

  • Made it 8 times larger (twice the length for each axis)
  • Separated the question-marks from the rest of the cube to make it printable with 2 materials/colors (I personally chose red for the box and white for the question-marks)
  • And with the coin-slot size is corrected for the largest Kuwaiti-currency coin (100 fils).

This is a present from me to my eldest son for losing is first tooth :)

Updated 25-09-2016:

  • Separated the box and lid into several files, for convenience.
  • Made the box wall a little thinner without compromising structural integrity, to save time and filament.
  • Corrected the size of the coin-hole.
  • Corrected fitment of lid.
  • Corrected the lid platform so that it doesn't string without supports.

Notes:
  • Printed the cube with e-Sun PLA (i.e. regular PLA), with the hot-end temperature at 215c, and the bed at 60c.
  • Use at least 2 parameters for the shell.
  • The software used was Cura-BCN3D V0.1.5-beta2 for slicing, so I had my limitations too, such as having only straight-line type infill, you might experiment with other types of course.
  • Given that the contact surface of the box is relatively large, it will be more prone to warping/lifting, and if not, be ready to take your time removing it without damaging your print-bed.

Sanding the sides of the lid might be necessary for you to make it fit the top of the box, but if you find yourself needing it to be sanded don't overdo it, it needs to fit snugly so that if you flip it while it's full the lid doesn't fall off.

description.text:
Having trouble with my overhangs... help?

EDIT: I originally posted this to link some pictures in a post to a group, not realizing that people would find it that didn't come from the group lol. So here is the original post so this makes more sense.

I got a Da Vinci 1.0a a few weeks ago and promptly flashed repetier and got some hatchbox abs. Everything has been printing beautifully with the exception of overhangs and I just cannot figure out why! You can see some examples in the pictures above.

At first I thought that I was printing too hot and fast since those shelf support pieces were pretty small, but then the 3 pieces that make up a phone camera stand were all printed simultaneously and you can see that all the layers where the major overhang on the tall piece is seemed to mess up everything else... maybe due to the plastic having too much time to cool and curling? Both of these prints ran while I was away so I didn't get to see what the actual problem was during the print.

Does anyone have any suggestions or tips on how to improve the overhangs?

I do have a cooling fan mounted on the extruder that blows at the print and is controlled with slic3r. If it helps, my main slic3r settings are:
Layer height: 0.2 (or 0.1 for high quality)
Perimeters: 3
Infill: 20-30% depending on print
Perimeter speed: 40
Small Perimeters: 25
External Perimeters: 90%
Supports: No
Rafts: No

comments.text:
at first i would recommend to turn the blower off. (no need/ not wanted for abs as it speeds up any warping by cooling down the material to soon and you want it as hot as possible till the end for best bed adhesion till the end) it makes sense for pla but no good material. wouldnt touch it.
second is maybe your bridging multiplier set to high. if its 1,0 try 0,95
or maybe your normal extrusion multiplier(flowrate) causes your issues
or maybe your speed settings are set to high... (external perimeters (90%) more than twice the speed as normal ones (40%) dont know but think external perimeters are individually for each thing and dont know if they are adjustable. i would try 50-60%) or maybe your overall speed is to high
u said u are printing hatchbox abs but not your temperatures

Hardware Installation
  1. Remove old spool holders.
  2. Thread the wires of the load cell through the base of the spool holder and insert the load cell into the base. The wires need to be on the side of the base with the hole.
  3. Insert M10 nut into the side of the base where the wires for the load cell are coming out.
  4. Using the bolt from old spool holder, tighten down the base such that the directional arrow on the outer edge of the load cell is pointing straight down. You shouldn't be able to turn it the base afterwards.
    • If you are having problems tightening it at the right angle, try rotating the M10 nut in the base.
  5. Insert a M8 nut into the slot on the side of the spool_holder-inner_bearing.stl.
  6. Slide the inner bearing piece over the outside of the load cell and secure it with another M5 screw.
  7. Press the bearings into the spool_holder-spacer.stl pieces.
  8. Press a bearing onto the spool_holder-inner_bearing.stl piece.
  9. Press a bearing onto the spool_holder-outer_bearing.stl piece.
  10. Thread another nut onto the threaded rod and thread it into the first nut in the spool base. Tighten the second nut to prevent the rod from spinning.
  11. Slide the PVC section over the spacers and thread the rob into the outer piece.
  12. Lock the outer piece with the final nut.

Printed parts
  • 2x spool_holder-base.stl
  • 2x spool_holder-inner_bearing.stl
  • 2x spool_holder-outer_bearing.stl
  • 2x spool_holder-spacer.stl
Other hardware
  • 2x 5 KG load cell
  • 1x Hx711 control board or equivalent board that can read two load cells
  • 4x M5 16mm button head screws
  • 2x M10 nuts
    • My Qidi Tech used M10 bolts with a pitch of 1.5, but use what ever matches your printer.
  • 4x 15mm ID, 35mm OD, 11mm thick, ball bearings
  • 2x threaded rod (designed for this rod)
  • 8x M8 nuts matching rod's thread pitch
  • 2x PVC tube

description.text:
Mount for Dremel Multipro 395

...for a MPCNC using the Universal Tool-Mount Plate I also made for it.

With/out -Support

The version with support in the filenames is with build-in supports. The other version is if you like to print without or use your own support system

Parts

  • There is the Dremel Main Mount part.
  • A Wide Clamp and the Front Clamp
  • The Front Ring you screw onto the threadding of your Dremel instead of the Dremel end.

Planned Additions
I am going to design a cable-holder/manager for the AC cable of the Dremel to be attached to the top of the Z-axis.
It is going to be universal though, so it will be posted seperately.

Printer:

My Crossbot design

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

44 or higher

Notes:
  • I used 0.4mm nozzle
  • 3 perimeters
  • 3 bottom/top
  • 44% infill (higher is better)
  • Use strong infill pattern: I used Tethrahedral in Cura 2.3
  • I have printed it without support with high speed fans, so it is doable, but it's easier to just use the version with build-in support

Parts cleanup.

Intentioanlly tight tolerances
There is a 0,2mm space between each hinge-parts. It means you might at first be unable to put them together if you have slight overextrude or just by normal Filament contraction.

Why?
I didn't want any wobble in the hinges.

M4 lock-nuts insertion into the Mount
Use a small plier to hold the lock-nuts and use a M4 screw to tighten up the nuts into the holes made for them in the Dremel Main Mount.
1 for each clamping mechanism.

BOM
  • 4x m4 20mm screws to fix the plate to tool-mount
  • 3x m4 20mm screws for the clasping system
  • 2x m4 lock-nuts for the clasping locking-system
  • 1x m4 35mm screw or equivalant m3 threadding for large clamp.
  • 1-2 m4 lock-nuts for large clamp.

Total:

  • 7x m4 20mm screws
  • 1x m4 35mm screw / 40ish m4 threaded rod.
  • 3-4 m4 lock nuts

description.text:
So, while i haven't really worked on my big t-slot based 2' x 2' 3D printer and/or CNC Mill that i'm building [designing] from scratch very much lately, i have recently been bugged that it is so large with no easy way to move it with handles or wheels (i may design a wheel system in the future). This handle is designed to fit 10 Series (10S) size 80/20 brand extruded tslot.

The design is as simple as it gets, but it should work great. Strength will be determined by how much infill you decide to print it at. I tried printing a test piece at default 20% infill, and under heavy testing it broke. So i would suggest printing yours at 40% percent infill for adequate strength. I have included teaser pictures for my 1010 t-slot compatible Nema23 motor mount that i designed for the same home designed t-slot based cnc machine. title: Ergo iPhone 6 Plus Case - For Limited Hand Mobility
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
It's taken a while to think of something that would benefit someone with limited hand mobility that:

a) isn't super complicated

b) isn't cumbersome

c) is created for the purposes of creating something rather than addressing a specific need

I spent a morning with taped up hands, and went about my day, and by far the trickiest thing was getting to grips with my iPhone 6 Plus. I love my iPhone and not being able to use it well made my face sad :(

Behold, the solution to (at least my) problem, the ergo iPhone case!

With the easy grip side handle you're able to hold the iPhone easily whilst using your other hand the operate it. Not only is there a side handle, there are also 3 finger holes to allow customised gripping

The iPhone case was designed from scratch, starting with the Apple official guidelines for accessory design. This case adhere's to all of them so buttons are easily accessed, the camera is usable and no connector sockets are obstructed.

Even 3D printed this is a perfect snap fit.

So did i address my initial questions? yes, yes i did

a) It's super simple, elegant design. no moving parts, no assembly.

b) it hardly adds any weight and is barely bigger than the iPhone itself but is super durable

c) It was designed to meet the requirements of one problem, not a jack of all trades device. iPhone 6 Plus is big! but now it's accessible to anyone regardless of their hand moblity (i'm keeping mine on my phone BTW!)

I printed me case in a splendid bright orange PLA

Settings were

Layer Res - 200micron

Print temp - Layer 1 - 220C all others 200C

HPB - 52C

Speed 70mm/s

Infil - 100%

NOTES:

This is designed for the iPhone 6 Plus, other variants can be designed upon request

I am right handed, so i have designed the case to be held in my left hand - A left handed version can also be designed upon request

An Apple TV v2 VESA bracket for mounting to to the back of a TV. Includes a place to wind up the cord, and a shelf for holding an HD OTA Antenna.

I picked up an Apple TV to use with a small LCD TV to watch media around the house. I wanted to mount the Apple TV to the VESA mount on the back of the TV, and also have a way to easily carry the TV around. After the initial design I decided I'd like a place to mount the OTA antenna and wind up the power cord.  
The bracket uses a standard 75mmx75mm VESA mount, M4 screws. The cord holder also uses M4 screws. Everything else is setup for M3 screws.  
The posts for the cord holders have an off-center hole that matches with the cord keeper, putting a pin in there will keep it from rotating.  
I need to update the file and add a place for putting a pin between the post and the back bracket.  
After mounting it to the TV I also realized I need to make the hole for the handle a little bigger, it can be a bit of a knuckle buster.  
The Apple TV is a lose fit, and will fall through, I put a piece of non-skid mat between the top bracket and the Apple TV before I tighten the screws down and that holds it in place.  
Created in SketchUp and then exported to STLs, also exported a DXF so a buddy could mill this for me out of Delrin. I assume it could just as easily be 3D printed.  
You'll need 2 side brackets, 2 cord winders (posts) and 2 cord keepers.

title: Handlebar mount adapter for scooter, motorcycle (for phone cradles etc)

description.text:
This mount allows you to use phone and GPS cradles with handlebar mounts on scooters with no handlebars. It attaches to a right mirror post. Due to vibration and stress, it needs to be reinforced with a T-shaped piece of metal underneath, otherwise plastic will most likely break.

I used this mount with iOttie Active Edge mount and it works great!
(http://www.iottie.com/Product/Detail/1619/iOttie-Active-Edge-Bar-Grip-Mount-For-Bike-And-Motorcycle-_-Black)

BOM:

  1. 6 in. x 5 in. 14-Gauge T Strap, found at Home Depot, part #461407
  2. Epoxy, I used a 5 minute one from Harbor Freight
  3. Washer (will add description)
  4. (Optional) Socket set screw (will add description)
  5. Your preferred cutoff tool, a few clamps, a drill with a large drill bit

Printer:

Wanhao i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

40%+

Notes:

Make sure to supports are enabled for "everywhere", not just touching the build plate: the crossbar needs to be printed with supports for obvious reasons. I printed with PETG, but ABS would probably work just as well. I don't think PLA would be strong enough. I printed with 40% infill, since I don't think adding more infill makes it any stronger.

After the print
  1. Take the T strap and hold it to the bottom of the printed part.
  2. Mark the lines where the T strap needs to be cut - the "wings" of the strap should be near the center of the wider part of the print, and the stem of the strap should align with the longer part of the print.
  3. Cut the T strap with a hacksaw, dremel, oscillating multitool etc.
  4. Mix some epoxy, apply to the bottom of the printed part and clamp the T strap to the part.
  5. I also applied epoxy to the print itself to reinforce the parts under most stress (see picture).
  6. After the epoxy is fully dry, drill out a hole in the metal to match the hole in the print.
  7. To mount, insert the washer into the indentation, then take a mirror and insert it through the mount. Screw the mirror into the mirror post, clamping the mount in between. Align the mirror and tighten the nut at the top to secure the whole thing.
  8. If you're using iOttie Active Edge, you'll notice that the provided thumbscrew will prevent you from lowering the mount past a certain angle. If you'd like to tilt the cradle lower, you'll need to discard the thumbscrew and buy a socket screw mentioned in the BOM to replace it.

title: A strappy laser-cut iPhone 5 stand
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This is a laser-cut iPhone stand I made on a laser cutter out of silicone. Turns out that silicone is a terrible material to laser-cut – it's very heat-resistant – and I had to finish it off with a craft knife. It did engrave nicely, though. I used 4mm silicone. I'd seen a friend's stand that was a rubber strap, but couldn't find somewhere to buy one. So I made one instead. It works OK, but isn't all that useful – iOS doesn't have a landscape mode on the iPhone, and a lot of apps don't have one either. I also find my iPad way more useful as a second screen. That said, the nice thing about a rubber strap stand is that it's super-cheap, it's very robust so you can just throw it in your bag or pencil case, and it's got a high coefficient of friction so your phone won't skitter around your desk if you try to use it by touch. I wrote some more about this stand on my blog.

remixed_from.title: DIY hydro drip bucket with 3D printed drip ring

description.text:
Easy to make and far cheaper than the commercial variety. Works with a standard aquarium air pump. In addition to printing the drip ring, you will need:

14" PVC pipe 1/2" OD with a 45 degree slant cut at one end
14" Clear Vinyl Hose 1/2" OD 3/8" ID
15" Clear Vinyl Hose 5/16" OD 3/16" ID
1 x Aquarium air pump
6' Air pump tubing
E6000 glue

Basically, the the the thin vinyl hose goes inside the thick vinyl hose all the way down until there's about 1/4" to the end of the outer hose. The end of the thin hose needs to be completely contained by the outer hose, but as close to the bottom of the bucket as possible. The air pump hose gets jammed into the wide hose at the top along with the thin hose and try to get it down inside a good 1/4". Try to orient the thin vinyl hose and the air pump hose so that their natural curves point away from each other. You should have about 1" of thin tube and 6' air pump hose sticking out the top of your wide hose. Completely cover that end with E6000 and allow to harden for 24 hours before use. Then, pop the drip ring on the end of the thin vinyl tube and slide the entire wide hose assembly into the PVC with the slanted end at the bottom.

title: Adjustable Z Endstop for Prusa i3

description.text:
One of the early modifications I made to my printer (Hesine M505 Prusa i3) was to add an adjustable Z endstop (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1253186 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:149882). The endstop worked well until I upgraded my X axis (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1103976). With the new X motor mount, the Z plunger no longer lined up with the endstop switch. I create a design based roughly on the original endstop mount that would align with the new X motor mount. I then decided to redesign the offset adjustment plunger mount to add a better switch contact (previously it was just the end of the adjustment screw) and screw tensioning. This thing is the result.

The Z endstop and offset mounts are fairly simple, just install per the attached images. The plunger may require a bit of explanation as some components are internal and not visible in the images. I believe that the adjustment screw and associated nuts are #6. I sourced them according to the original design, and don't recall specifically. The screw I used is around 3 inches long. To assemble the offset mount, screw a nut onto the adjustment screw so that about 5mm of thread extends past the nut. Put another nut into the bottom of the mount. Place a small section (about 8mm) of 3/8" compression spring over the end of the screw so that it rests on the nut. Insert this assembly into the top of the mount, compress the spring and screw into the nut on the bottom of the mount. For the plunger (the part that contacts the switch), install a nut into the recessed area and then glue the bottom piece in place. This traps the nut inside the assembly. Then screw another nut onto the end of the adjustment screw with about 4mm of thread extending past the nut. Screw the plunger assembly onto the end of the screw and use the nut to tighten in place. You will need to screw the adjustment screw in as far as it will go in order to access the mount holes to attach the offset assembly to the X axis motor mount.

description.text: This is a remix of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:131656 to fit the bed of a Solidoodle 2 (rather than a Solidoodle 3). The Nozzle_cleaner.stl file included here is from the original thing, but has been flipped over. The cleaner.scad file is openscad that imports that stl, cuts it up, and joins it back together as a shorter piece that fits the Solidoodle 2. This updated version includes two flavors. One that is plain (same as original) and one that has an M3 nut trap so a M3 bolt can be used to hold it in place more securely than wedging in pieces of paper. Now, I've added a 3rd update with newcleaner.stl and newcleaner.scad. This is a complete redesign which will hopefully cling to the aluminum bracket better, and it provides multiple pipe cleaner loops since one sometimes didn't work. More info is available at http://tomhorsley.com/hardware/solidoodle/solidoodle-cleaner.html
